Functions (Methods) in Java
In Java, functions are called methods because they are always defined inside a class.
What is a Function (Method)?
A method is a block of code that performs a specific task. It is used to avoid code repetition and improve readability.
Syntax
Java
returnType methodName(parameters) {
    // method body
}
returnType → Type of value returned (int, String, void, etc.)
methodName → Name of the method
parameters → Input values passed to the method
Example 1: Method without Parameters and Return Type
Java
public class Main {

    static void greet() {
        System.out.println("Welcome to Java");
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        greet();
    }
}
Output
Plain text
Welcome to Java
Example 2: Method with Parameters
Java
public class Main {

    static void add(int a, int b) {
        System.out.println(a + b);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        add(10, 20);
    }
}
Output
Plain text
30
Example 3: Method with Return Type
Java
public class Main {

    static int add(int a, int b) {
        return a + b;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int result = add(10, 20);
        System.out.println(result);
    }
}
Output
Plain text
30
Types of Methods in Java
1. Predefined Methods
Methods already available in Java libraries.
Example:
Java
String name = "Java";

System.out.println(name.length());
System.out.println(Math.sqrt(25));
2. User-Defined Methods
Methods created by programmers.
Example:
Java
static void display() {
    System.out.println("Hello");
}
Four Types of Methods
1. No Parameters, No Return Value
Java
static void show() {
    System.out.println("Hello");
}
2. Parameters, No Return Value
Java
static void display(String name) {
    System.out.println(name);
}
3. No Parameters, Return Value
Java
static int getNumber() {
    return 100;
}
4. Parameters and Return Value
Java
static int multiply(int a, int b) {
    return a * b;
}
Method Overloading
Two or more methods with the same name but different parameters.
Java
class Demo {

    void add(int a, int b) {
        System.out.println(a + b);
    }

    void add(int a, int b, int c) {
        System.out.println(a + b + c);
    }
}
Why Do We Use Methods?
Without methods:
Plain text
Calculate area
Calculate area
Calculate area
The same code is repeated.
With methods:
Java
calculateArea();
